The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
 Saturday, April 24, 2004  The City Diary
																																																		Ten-year-old Sudipto Maji was crushed under the wheels of a lorry at Kachharipara in the Bagnan police station area of Howrah on Friday afternoon. The boy, a resident of Hijal-chak, was returning home from school with his maternal grandfather, Joydeb Nayek. The two, riding a bicycle, were about to cross the Manpur crossing when the lorry speeded up and ran them down. 																																																								eading towards Howrah town, the lorry carrying plastic sheets was trying to overtake another vehicle. While Sudipto died on the spot, his grandfather was taken to a nearby hospital with multiple injuries. The boy was smashed beyond recognition, said a police officer. Bystanders stopped the vehicle and set it on fire. The lorry driver and his assistant have been arrested, police said. Residents put up a roadblock for hours to protest the accident.																																																		Sheikh Munna, a 45-year-old resident of Metiabruz who was arrested in a petty case on April 4, died in jail custody on Friday. He was produced in the Alipore sub-divisional judicial magistrates court on April 5. On Wednesday, he had taken ill and was admitted to MR Bangur Hospital, where he died on Friday. But Trinamul Congress MLA Sougata Roy alleged that Munna died in the Rabindranagar police station lock-up after he was beaten up by police. Trinamul Congress workers gheraoed the police station on Friday night in protest.																																																		A division bench of Calcutta High Court, led by Chief Justice A.K. Mathur, on Friday stayed a notification of the West Bengal Pollution Control Board dated March 3, 2004, restraining political parties from using loudspeakers during election campaign while the Higher Secondary examinations are on. The order followed a petition by Trinamul Congress MLA Arunava Ghosh. 																																																		Sunderbans development minister and CPM MLA from Mathurapur Kanti Ganguly on Friday filed a suit in the chief judicial magistrates court in Alipore against former CPM MLA and Trinamul Congress Lok Sabha candidate from Mathurapur, Radhika Ranjan Pramanik. Pramanik had accused Ganguly of siphoning Rs 4 lakh, which the Trinamul candidate claimed he had donated from his MPs local area development fund to Raidighi College. Ganguly has rubbished the charge. The matter will come up for hearing on May 7.																																																		The body of an unidentified 30-year-old man was found beside a canal at Garpara in Dankuni on Friday evening. Residents noticed the body with injury marks and informed the police. 																																																		Calcutta High Court on Friday directed the collector of state excise to hold a meeting with petitioner Utpal Roy and others, and take action in accordance with law against a bar-cum-restaurant on Elgin Road. Roy, representing an NGO, said the excise department had no right to issue bar licence within 300 feet of educational institutions and places of worship. The bar-cum-restaurant concerned is located close to Calcutta International School, Bhawanipur Education Society and Netaji Institute. 																																																		Information technology major Wipro on Friday launched Wipro Applying Thought in Schools. The project, aimed at effecting changes in the education system by imparting training to teachers, will be rolled out in association with Vikramshila Education Resource Society. Several school principals attended a round-table on Quality Education in a Changing Context organised as part of the launching ceremony.																																																		A tax bar association filed a petition in the high court on behalf of at least 600 clients on Friday, saying that the income tax authorities were not issuing PAN cards to them. Petitioners lawyer Subroto Mookherjee said several people who had applied for PAN cards in 1998 are yet to receive them.TO Sarada Seva Sangha, Shibpur, for introducing a free text-book section in the library
